d the on-going Cold War. As the century went on, there were more scientists - requiring more money to fund their research - occupying ever more niches in industry, academia, military and civil institutions. Combining the latest research on twentieth-century British science with insightful discussion of what it meant to govern - and govern with - science, this volume provides both an invaluable introduction to science in twentieth-century Britain for students and a fresh thematic focus on science and government for researchers interested in the histories of science and governance. This volume features a foreword from Sir John Beddington, UK Government Chief Scientific Adviser 2008-13.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aScience and state. 0aTechnology and state. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh  aBritain.  aGovernance.  aOrganisation.  aPolitics.  aPure and applied science.  aScience.  aTwentieth century.1 aAgar, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnthony, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalmer, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalver,  Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharnley, Berris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDesmarais, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodchild, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorrocks, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLean, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeggett, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a